  "doc_id": "41846",
  "text": "Another larvae that showed low specificity was the nematode Contracaecum sp. This species belongs to the family Anisakidae and is of great importance in public health because of its high zoonotic potential. Anisakids are important to humans on a number of counts: economically, politically and mainly pathologically. Paratenic hosts are often fish that are important for human consumption. The worms do not mature in humans and the pathology is mostly associated with penetration of the small intestine and stomach by the larvae. The degree of discomfort is likely a consequence of the number of larvae penetrating. In rare cases, humans have died from anisakiasis due to severe peritonitis [CITATION_1] ). However, there are no records of this zoonosis in the region and this is probably due to the fact that all of the larvae of this species were encysted in the mesentery, which is not used for human consumption.",
